> We're big fans of pan sauces because they're an easy way to make a great dish completely irresistible. Here, peach jam, rich chicken stock, tangy Dijon, and fresh thyme mingle to create a condiment that you'll want to drizzle over everything. Speaking of, along with the juicy pork cutlets, we're serving up sides of garlicky, almond-flecked couscous and simply roasted zucchini for maximum dinnertime deliciousness.

Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Wash and dry all produce.

Peel and mince @garlic{1%clove}. Trim and halve @zucchini{1}, cut crosswise into ½-inch-thick
half-moons. Strip @thyme{¼%ounce} leaves from stems until you have 1 1/2 tsp (1 TBSP for 4
servings); mince leaves. Zest and quarter @lemon{1}.

In a #small bowl{}, whisk together @water{¼%cup} (1/3 cup for 4), @peach jam{2%tablespoon},
@chicken stock concentrate{1}, minced thyme, and half the @dijon mustard{1%teaspoon} (all for 4).

Heat a #small pot{} over medium high heat; add @sliced almonds{½%ounce} and cook, stirring
occasionally, until golden and fragrant, ~{2-4%minutes}.

Add a drizzle of @olive oil{1%teaspoon}, garlic, @Israeli couscous{2.5%ounce}, and a big
pinch of @salt{}; cook, stirring, ~{30%seconds}.

Stir in @water{¾%cup} (1 1/2 cups for 4 servings) and cover. Bring to a boil, then
immediately reduce heat to low. Simmer, covered, until couscous is tender, ~{6-8%minutes}.
If necessary, drain any excess water from #pot{}. Keep covered off heat until ready to
serve.

While couscous cooks, toss zucchini on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @olive oil{},
@salt{}, and @pepper{}. Roast on top rack, flipping halfway through, until browned and
tender, ~{14-16%minutes}.

Pat @pork cutlets{12%ounce} dry with #paper towels{} and season generously all over with
@salt{} and @pepper{}.

Melt @butter{1%tablespoon} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add pork and cook
until browned and cooked through, ~{2-3%minutes} per side. (For 4 servings, cook in 2
batches, adding another 1 TBSP butter with second batch if necessary.) Turn off heat;
transfer to a #plate{}. Wipe out pan.

Heat same pan over medium-high heat. Pour in sauce. Bring to a simmer and cook, stirring,
until thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Turn off heat and stir in @butter{1%tablespoon} (2 TBSP for 4 servings). Taste and
season with a squeeze of lemon juice, @salt{}, and @pepper{}. Return pork to pan, turning
a few times to coat.

Stir @butter{1%tablespoon} into pot with couscous; season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.
Toss zucchini with lemon zest.

> TIP: If necessary, heat couscous over low heat with a splash of water, stirring,
> until warmed through.

Divide pork, zucchini, and couscous between plates. Drizzle any remaining sauce from pan
over pork. Serve remaining lemon wedges on the side.